# Emily Async & Performance Rules

## Core Async Rules
- Never do blocking I/O in an async function — use `await asyncio.to_thread(sync_fn)` for file I/O, CPU-heavy work, or sync libraries
- All route handlers, agent methods, bus callbacks, and provider streams must be `async def`
- Use `async for` when consuming async iterators (provider streams, DB cursors)
- Use `async with` for httpx clients, DB connections, and ZeroMQ sockets

## Concurrency Patterns
- `asyncio.gather(*coros)` for independent parallel tasks (e.g., fetching from multiple providers)
- `asyncio.TaskGroup` (Python 3.11+) for structured concurrency with proper error propagation
- `asyncio.Queue` for producer-consumer patterns (perception bus, agent bus)
- `asyncio.Event` for signaling between tasks (interrupt flags, shutdown signals)
- `asyncio.Semaphore` to limit concurrent access to constrained resources (VRAM, API rate limits)

## Event Loop Safety
- Never call `asyncio.run()` inside an already-running loop — use `asyncio.create_task()` or `loop.run_in_executor()`
- Never use `time.sleep()` in async code — use `await asyncio.sleep()`
- ZeroMQ must use `zmq.asyncio.Context` — never sync `zmq.Context` in async code
- Avoid `loop.run_until_complete()` in async contexts — it's for sync entry points only

## HTTP Clients
- Reuse `httpx.AsyncClient` instances (one per provider) — never create per-request
- Set explicit `httpx.Timeout(total, connect=)` — default infinite timeout is a production hazard
- Use `async with client.stream("POST", url, json=body) as response:` for SSE consumption
- Close clients in shutdown/cleanup — unclosed clients leak file descriptors

## Database
- Use `aiosqlite` for all SQLite operations — never `sqlite3` directly in async code
- Pool connections where possible; single-connection SQLite should serialize via an asyncio lock
- Use `asyncio.to_thread` for heavy query result processing

## Caching
- `functools.lru_cache` / `@cache` for pure functions with hashable args (model lookups, regex compilation)
- Provider instances cached in module-level dicts with lazy construction
- Consider TTL caches (`cachetools.TTLCache`) for external data that expires

## Memory Efficiency
- Use async generators (`async def stream() -> AsyncIterator[Chunk]`) for streaming — never buffer entire responses
- Use `collections.deque(maxlen=N)` for bounded buffers (sensory buffer, log ring)
- Release large objects (model tensors, audio buffers) explicitly when done — don't wait for GC

## VRAM Management
- Check VRAM headroom before loading models — `torch.cuda.mem_get_info()` or `nvidia-smi`
- Unload idle models to free VRAM for active ones — the model router manages this
- Use float16/bfloat16 inference where possible to halve VRAM usage
- Pin frequently-used small models (nano, embedding) and swap larger ones

## Latency Budget Targets
- Wake word detection: < 50ms
- VAD per chunk: < 1ms
- STT (Faster-Whisper): < 300ms
- LLM first token (fast model): < 1s
- LLM first token (nano model): < 100ms
- TTS first audio byte: < 200ms
- End-to-end voice response: < 2s
